'''Carolyn Burke''' (born 1940<ref name=GreenwoodH-2006-01-07>{{citation |title=Shoot for Success |author=Greenwood, Helen |date=January 7, 2006 |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] }}</ref>), is an [[Australian people|Australian]]-born [[United States|American]] [[biographer]], [[art critic]], and [[translator]]. Her main focus is on feminist studies and strong independent artistic women of the 1920s through the 1940s.
Born in Sydney, Australia, she lived in Philadelphia and spent many years in [[Paris]], and now lives in [[Santa Cruz, California]].<ref name=GreenwoodH-2006-01-07/>
Burke has taught at [[Princeton University|Princeton]] and the [[University of California at Santa Cruz]] and at [[University of California, Davis|Davis]]; at the Universities of [[University of Western Sydney|Western Sydney]] and [[University of New South Wales|New South Wales]] in [[Australia]]; and at [[the Sorbonne]] and the [[Université Lille Nord de France|University of Lille]] in [[France]].
She is the author of ''Becoming Modern: The Life of Mina Loy'' (1996), about the [[Mina Loy|noted poet]], which earned prominent reviews in ''[[The New York Times]]'', ''[[The Washington Post]]'', ''[[The Atlantic]]'', ''[[The New Republic]]'' and ''[[The Nation]]''. Burke's work ''Lee Miller: A Life'' (2005) was a [[New York Times Notable Book of the Year]] and a finalist for [[National Book Critics Circle Award|The National Book Critics Circle Biography award]] about the [[Lee Miller|model turned photographer]], And her book about the iconic [[Edith Piaf|French chanteuse]] entitled ''No Regrets: The Life of Edith Piaf'' (2011).
Burke has spoken at writers’ festivals and literary events in the [[United States|U.S.]], [[United Kingdom|U.K.]], [[France]], and Australia. Her appearances include campuses (Princeton, [[Getty Research Institute]], [[New York University]]’s Maison Française, University of New South Wales, [[University of Sydney]]); radio and television in [[San Francisco]], [[New York City]], and [[Sydney]]; and cultural groups ([[National Arts Club]], New York; [[Metropolitan Club]], San Francisco; [[Lyceum Club (Australia)|Lyceum Club]], Sydney; [[Monterey Museum of Art]], [[San Jose Museum of Art]]).
