{{Infobox artist | name = Lillian Friedman Astor | image = Photo of Lillian Friedman Astor.jpg | imagesize = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth date|1912|4|12|mf=y}} | birth_place = New York, New York | death_date = {{death date and age|1989|7|9|1912|4|12|mf=y}} | death_place = | nationality = [[United States|American]] | education = | field = [[Animation]] | training = | movement = | works = | patrons = | awards = | spouse = }}
'''Lillian Friedman Astor''' (born April 12, 1912 in [[New York City]]&nbsp;– July 9, 1989) was the first American female studio animator, working at for the [[Fleischer Studios|Fleischer Brothers' studio]], [[inker|inking]] and eventually animating various [[Betty Boop]] cartoons, as well as one [[Popeye]], some Color Classics, and several [[Hunky and Spunky]] cartoons, although she received screen credit on only six cartoons in her lifetime.<ref>''Who's Who in Animated Cartoons: An International Guide to Film & Television's Award-Winning and Legendary Animators'', by Jeff Lenburg, pp. 95–97</ref>
== Personal life ==
She attended [[Washington Irving High School (New York City)|Washington Irving High School]] where she studied animation and fashion design. After graduating she worked as a fashion designer.<ref>''Who's Who in Animated Cartoons: An International Guide to Film & Television's Award-Winning and Legendary Animators'', by Jeff Lenburg, p. 96</ref>
== Animation career ==
After being rejected by Disney,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theanimatedcritique.blogspot.com/2008/05/lillian-friedman-rejected-from-disney.html|title=Gender and Race Critique in Animation: Lillian Friedman - Rejected from Disney|first=|last=Pineapplesauce|date=16 May 2008|website=theanimatedcritique.blogspot.com}}</ref> Friedman was hired by the [[Fleischer Studios]] in 1930 as an [[inker]]. Taken under the wing of Fleischer animator [[Shamus Culhane|James "Shamus" Culhane]], Friedman was promoted to his assistant and [[Inbetweening|in-betweener]], responsible for intermediate drawings between two images to give the appearance that the first image evolves smoothly into the second image, and giving the illusion of movement. Impressed by her skill, in 1933, Culhane "secretly" promoted Friedman to [[animator]] where she could generate animation content. Working on the crew of [[Myron Waldman]],<ref>Comment by Bob Jaques, NOVEMBER 17, 2007 at 9:11 AM, [http://popeyeanimators.blogspot.com/2007/10/lillian-friedman-astor-pioneer-woman.html http://popeyeanimators.blogspot.com/2007/10/lillian-friedman-astor-pioneer-woman.html]</ref> she animated – uncredited – a Popeye cartoon, ''[[Can You Take It]]'' (1934).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://popeyeanimators.blogspot.com/2007/10/lillian-friedman-astor-pioneer-woman.html|title=Popeye Cartoons (formerly Popeye Animators): Lillian Friedman (Astor) - Pioneer Woman Animator|first=Bob|last=Jaques|date=3 November 2007|website=popeyeanimators.blogspot.com}}</ref> Her animation work also appears in, ''[[Betty Boop's Prize Show]]'' (1934), ''[[Making Stars]]'' (1935), ''[[Judge for a Day]]'' (1935), ''[[Be Human (1936 cartoon)|Be Human]]'' (1936), ''[[The New Deal Show]]'' (1937), ''[[Pudgy Takes a Bow-Wow]]'' (1937), ''[[Buzzy Boop at the Concert]]'' (1938), ''[[The Lost Kitten|Pudgy and the Lost Kitten]]'' (1938), ''[[Honest Love and True]]'' (1938), and the [[Color Classics|Color Classic]] ''[[Hawaiian Birds]]'' (1936).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theanimatedcritique.blogspot.com/2008/05/lillian-friedman-first-female-american.html|title=Gender and Race Critique in Animation: Lillian Friedman - First Female American Animator!|first=|last=Pineapplesauce|date=16 May 2008|website=theanimatedcritique.blogspot.com}}</ref> She was also responsible for animating several scenes in ''[[Popeye the Sailor Meets Sindbad the Sailor]]'' in 1936, specifically when Popeye give the "twisker" punch and the two-headed giant, "Boola"<ref>Article from Paramount promotional booklet for "Popeye The Sailor Meets Sindbad the Sailor" 1936, see [http://seymourkneitel.blogspot.com/2012/05/first-woman-animator.html http://seymourkneitel.blogspot.com/2012/05/first-woman-animator.html]</ref>
